					<span class="printuser avatarhover"><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/lackwit" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(616788); return false;"  ><img class="small" src="http://www.wikidot.com/avatar.php?userid=616788&amp;amp;size=small&amp;amp;timestamp=1610203527" alt="Lackwit" style="background-image:url(http://www.wikidot.com/userkarma.php?u=616788)"/></a><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/lackwit" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(616788); return false;" >Lackwit</a></span> <span class="odate time_1501081200 format_%25e%20%25b%20%25Y%2C%20%25H%3A%25M%7Cagohover">26 Jul 2017 15:00</span>
														</div>
			</div>
			<div class="content" id="post-content-3558384">
									

<p>Very much gave me the feeling of a <em>Back to the Future II</em>-style take on Foundation future-history. The fact that it seems a little &quot;sterilized&quot; helps create the impression of a somewhat stuffy museum tour even though the (doubtlessly somewhat anomalous) tourists are frequently reminded that any injuries will be reversed afterward.</p>
<p>There is a sort of blandness to this vision that I think follows naturally from the present-day Foundation's mission of preserving baseline consensus reality. We only get glimpses of what an exciting world exists beyond the Disneyland-monorail tour that happens to have a personal hell dimension as a stop. I like the effect this creates. Well done.</p>

							</div>

								
					
